  title: Memorial on the Duties of the Prime Minister
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The office of Prime Minister gathers all responsibilities of the realm. Therefore, as the ancient scholar Stone-Introducer said: "Above, one harmonizes yin and yang; below, one pacifies the common people. Rewards and punishments are the pivot of statecraft; policies and edicts flow from this source." I believe the Prime Minister's duty rests on these four pillars, but above all on rewards and punishments.

    To harmonize yin and yang does not mean they balance themselves without action. When rewards match merit, the virtuous are encouraged. When punishments fit the crime, the wicked are deterred. The gravest crime is treason. Those who suppressed the Wang clan and elevated Changwang, who invited Sinwu and severed the Wang line—these are the supreme traitors, the very heads of rebellion. Yet they escape heaven's judgment for years now. They adorn themselves, gather followers, move freely through palace and realm, showing no restraint. Their children and nephews fill high posts with none daring to question them. How then can those of us holding the Prime Minister's office and wielding reward and punishment evade our responsibility?

    We must lay bare their crimes before the Sovereign, inform the people, and report to the Great Temple. Only after numbering their sins and executing justice will the spirits above find peace, the people's grievance be redressed, heaven and earth's order be restored, and the Prime Minister's duty be fulfilled.

    If one says, "A man's guilt is not my concern. Life and death rest with the sovereign alone. What has the Prime Minister to do with this?"—did not the Historian Donghu condemn Zhao Dun precisely because he failed to punish the regicide?

    In Spring and Autumn times, when Zhao Chuan of Jin assassinated his lord, the Historian Donghu recorded: "Zhao Dun slew his lord." Dun protested: "I did not slay him." The Historian replied: "As Prime Minister you could not flee beyond the realm, yet upon return you did not punish the traitor. Who then slew your lord but you?" Confucius said: "Donghu was a good historian. Zhao Dun was a good minister. Both bore reproach for the sake of law."

    Thus Dun, though Prime Minister, could not punish the regicide, yet accepted the name of regicide without protest. Only then did the duty to eliminate traitors become solemn, and the conspiracy of rebels find no place between heaven and earth. Therefore it is said: rulers who do not understand the Spring and Autumn principle must bear the name of chief criminal; ministers who do not understand it must fall into the crime of treason and regicide. This is the meaning.

    Though I lack talent, I have been permitted to follow as Prime Minister and hear of state affairs. How dare I not fear the judgment of this good historian?

    Some say: "This criminal is a Confucian luminary; another is connected by marriage to the royal house. The law here is difficult to apply." But recall: when Lin Yan deposed the Yuan King and installed his brother Chuang, he first devised the scheme, then informed Attendant Li Zangyong. Zangyong, not knowing what to do, merely said "yes" and assented. Later, when the Yuan King was restored, Zangyong, though risen to Prime Minister, could not suppress the scheme or prevent the rebellion. He was stripped of office and made a commoner.

    Now, is Li Saek's status as Confucian luminary comparable to Zangyong's? Is his role in initiating the wicked scheme to suppress the Wang and elevate Changwang different from Zangyong merely assenting to Lin Yan's plot? The Master Hu said: "Of old, Lady Wenjiang aided in murdering Duke Huan; Lady Ajiang aided in murdering two lords. The Sage recorded their flight never to return, thus showing deep severance. This manifests that affection is light but righteousness is heavy."

    Those who slew Huan was Duke Xiang; those who slew two lords was Qingfu. Yet the Sage counted the two ladies as participants, severing them deeply and punishing them severely. The Successor King is born of the lady; yet she cannot let maternal affection override the great duty between sovereign and minister—how much less others?

    Some contend: "Though Shinwu is Shin-don's son, Hyonnung adopted him as his own, enfeoffed him Duke of Gangnyeong, and obtained the Son of Heaven's mandate. His lordship was thus established. As he became minister, it is gravely improper to drive him out." Yet the royal seat is the Taejo's seat; the realm is the Taejo's realm. How could Hyonnung privately dispose of them?

    Once Yanzi offered Yan to Zikuai. When asked if Yan could be punished, Mencius said: "No. Yanzi cannot give Yan to Zikuai, nor can Zikuai accept it from Yanzi." The Sage saw that land and people, received from former rulers, cannot be privately granted by the present king.

    When King Hui of Zhou altered succession through favoritism, Duke Huan of Qi assembled the lords and met the Crown Prince at Shoushi to confirm his position. Though the distinction between heir and concubine-born was great, both were the king's sons. Yet even the Son of Heaven could not privately grant the realm to a favored son; yet a mere duke, assembling the lords, opposed heaven's decree. The Sage deemed this righteous. Never did the Crown Prince refuse his father, nor Duke Huan his sovereign. This because heaven's justice is supreme. Could Hyonnung privately grant the Taejo's seat and people to a traitor's son?

    Moreover, the heavenly mandate was obtained through deception by a temporary usurper. Later, the Son of Heaven decreed: "The ruler of Koryo's line is broken. Though we borrowed the Wang to replace them, this was not the Three Han's wise counsel." Furthermore: "If a capable minister properly established lord and subject, the former mandate contains error, which heaven's son now corrects." How dare they cite the mandate as excuse?

    Regarding service as minister: The Chronicle records Shen Shiqi as Imperial Tutor, Zhou Bo and Chen Ping as Prime Ministers. Later it records that Han's great ministers executed the heir, installed King Heng as Emperor, then records "the Emperor" and "the Prime Minister"—is this not language of service? When it says "the ministers executed the heir," is this not language of eliminating traitors? Not only this: Wu Zetian ruled as Emperor long. Di Renjie recommended Zhang Jianzhi as Prime Minister. Jianzhi deposed Wu and installed Zhongzong. To recommend one as Prime Minister—is this not service? To depose Wu—is this not eliminating the traitor? Yet across a hundred generations, we honor Zhou Bo and Chen Ping for stabilizing Liu; we praise Zhang Jianzhi for restoring Tang. Never do we condemn them for serving while deposing their lord.

    Yet Li Saek and his associate, though insufficient in benevolence and righteousness, are learned scholars of antiquity. How could they not have heard these examples? Their stubborn delusion shows they fabricate false doctrine to confound the people. The former kings' law states that those spreading falsehoods to deceive the masses deserve death. How much more those who birth wicked doctrines to aid rebels?

    Some say: "That they invited Shinwu was because, with Changwang still weak, the Wang could never have revived without it." Yet true loyal ministers and righteous men, bearing heaven's decree, proposed removing the usurper to restore the Wang. The false Shinwu's faction first obtained the Bureau of Rites' notification, learning of heaven's will and righteous men's proposal. They then plotted to install Changwang's father to serve their private ambition—is this not precisely inviting Shinwu to sever the Wang?

    Some object: "You are their junior in learning and friendship. To attack so fiercely—is this not harsh?" Yet Su Shi, though junior to Master Zhu, was condemned by Zhu for daring heterodox views, destroying rites and corrupting teaching. Zhu rebuked him severely without mercy, saying: "I do not presume to censure ancients. As sage Tang said, 'I fear Heaven and dare not but act rightly,' so I too fear Heaven and dare not but speak truth." Su's crime was merely heterodoxy toward law. Yet Zhu, in his benevolence, compared it to Tang punishing Jie. How much more should we condemn those who party with usurpers and suppress the rightful Wang—these are the royal ancestors' criminals, the very enemy of teaching! Should we spare them for seniority? Moreover, Li Saek himself claimed dissent in the Muin year's succession, boasting that he suppressed the Wang as his achievement. Now that he elevates false Shinwu, does not this same measure apply?

    Some say: "You have already submitted memorial seeking retirement and written to the Sovereign regarding the criminals, now reporting to the temple—is this not excessive?" When Chen Heng slew his lord, Confucius bathed and attended court, saying: "Chen Heng slew his lord. I request his punishment." He also told his three disciples the same. The regicide was in Qi, seemingly unrelated to Lu. Confucius was already retired, seemingly unrelated to Lu's affairs. He had already petitioned his lord—must he also tell the disciples?

    Yet the Sage, in his magnanimous humility, petitioned his lord within and informed his disciples without, determined to see the criminal punished. This is because the regicide harms all men equally; heaven's hatred is universal. While dwelling in Lu, Confucius could not abide Qi's traitor—how much less endure his own state's? Though serving as minister after the great officers, he could not ignore a neighboring lord's affairs—how much less a royal traitor in his own realm?

    The Spring and Autumn records: "The people of Wei slew Zhou Xu." Master Hu explains: "'People' means the multitude; Stone Que devised it and had Right Minister Chou execute it. The text says 'people' to show all possessed righteous heart." Thus all share duty to eliminate traitors. Can the Prime Minister neglect this duty? Moreover, Stone Que killed his own son Hou for Zhou Xu's sake. The Gentlemen said: "Stone Que was a pure minister. Great righteousness eliminates even kinship." Thus traitors, whether near or distant, noble or base, all must be eliminated.

    Some object: "Chen Heng and Zhou Xu personally committed regicide and treason. But Li Saek and his associate never committed regicide. To equate them—is this not excessive? How do you know you do not falsely accuse them?"

    Yet Master Hu has already explained: Moving temples and changing the dynastic name—is this not worse than regicide? Those who party with usurpers and sever the Wang's sacrifices do precisely what Hu described: they move temples and eliminate the same clan. Their crime exceeds regicide alone.

    Of old, when great ministers faced accusation, they donned the prisoner's garb and begged forgiveness. Huo Guang, though honored as guardian under the Wu Emperor and instrumental in establishing the Zhao Emperor, when accused, dared not enter the palace but waited outside to clear himself. If one faces accusation, should one not approach officials tearfully, submit to questioning, and clarify one's innocence? Yet this one counseled his wife to submit memorial, feigned illness, sought physicians outside—how dare he not defend himself? This itself reveals guilt; surely his words fail him.

    The Spring and Autumn method of punishing traitors prosecutes them even when proof seems lacking, seeking their intent. How much more when evidence is clear?

    When Emperor Gaozong elevated Wu Zetian as Empress, both Chu Suiliang and Xu Jingzong served as Prime Ministers. Suiliang strongly opposed it, even unto death. Jingzong deferred to the Emperor: "This is a family matter, not for ministers to judge." Thus was Wu made Empress. Jingzong enjoyed wealth his lifetime. The Five Princes plotted restoration and all died alike. Looking back, Jingzong's strategy succeeded while Suiliang and the Princes failed. Yet Jingzong's brief wealth vanished like wind-blown dust, leaving no trace. But Suiliang and the Princes' noble names and righteous deeds shine eternally across history, existing with all the universe.

    Though I am base and clumsy, I shame Jingzong and admire Suiliang. The saying goes: "Those who scheme together must face death together." The Sovereign has not abandoned this foolish servant but permitted my participation in restoration. How dare I, from fear of wicked conspirators, remain silent and seek base survival?

    I beseech that we follow the Spring and Autumn method of punishing traitors, taking Confucius and Stone Que as our models. Then shall the state and its altars be secure.
